<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/2045> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:created "2018-09-10T16:07:43.000Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:modified "2021-03-30T14:11:50.521Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:altLabel "Chandrasekhar-Schonberg limit"@en , "Schoenberg-Chandrasekhar limit"@en , "Schönberg-Chandrasekhar limit"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/662> ;
	dcterms:creator <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Schonberg-Chandrasekhar limit"@en ;
	skos:related <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1599> ;
	skos:scopeNote "Not to be confused with the Chandrasekhar limit."@en ;
	skos:definition "During the main sequence stage, a star burns the hydrogen in its core and transforms it into helium. When the helium mass amounts to about 10% of the initial stellar mass, the star can no longer maintain the hydrostatic equilibrium in its core; the star increases its volume and leaves the main sequence in order to become a red giant."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/2046> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:created "2018-09-13T14:51:48.000Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:modified "2018-09-13T14:55:58.000Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/91> ;
	dcterms:creator <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Stellar evolutionary models"@en ;
	skos:narrower <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1600> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/725> ;
	skos:related <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1599> .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/2047> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:created "2018-09-13T14:54:24.000Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-10T19:11:26.949Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/725> ;
	dcterms:creator <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Main sequence"@en ;
	skos:related <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/2053> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1843> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1000> ;
	skos:definition "An evolutionary stage in the life of a star when it generates its energy by the conversion of hydrogen to helium via nuclear fusion in its core. Stars spend 90% of their life on the main sequence. On the Hertzsprung-Russell diagram it appears as a track running from top left (high temperature, high luminosity, high mass) to lower right (low temperature, low luminosity, low mass)."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/2048> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:created "2018-09-13T14:55:08.000Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-02T16:46:03.527Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/725> ;
	dcterms:creator <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Horizontal branch"@en ;
	skos:related <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/513> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1842> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/746> ;
	skos:definition "A set of roughly horizontal points in the Hertzsprung-Russell diagram of a typical globular cluster. It displays a stage of stellar evolution which immediately follows the red giant branch (RGB) in stars with an initial mass < 1.2 M_sun. When the star's ascent of the RGB is terminated by the helium flash, it moves down to the Horizontal Branch (HB). The star's effective temperature on the HB is higher than it was on the RGB, but the luminosity is considerably less than at the helium flash. Usually HB stars have two energy sources: in addition to the helium burning in their cores, they experience hydrogen fusion in a surrounding shell. The thickness of the shell determines the color of the HB stars. A thin shell, involving low opacity, makes the star look blue. The HB domain encompasses a very large effective temperature range with several members: extreme HB, blue HB, RR Lyrae, red HB, and red clump stars. The locations depend on many parameters, including stellar mass, metallicity, age, helium abundance, and rotation."@en .

