<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/64> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2022-06-24T17:23:45.950Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:altLabel "Ancient astronomy"@en , "Archeoastronomy"@en , "Astroarchaeology"@en , "Astroarcheology"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/2366> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Archaeoastronomy"@en ;
	skos:narrower <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1022> ;
	skos:related <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/433> ;
	skos:definition "The study that deals with the astronomical knowledge of prehistoric peoples (season events, calendars, observing sites, astronomical alignments) and its influence on their cultures and societies (mythologies, religions, life). Archaeoastronomy covers the intersection between astronomy and archaeology."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1023> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/103> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Megamasers"@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1024> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-10T19:22:32.883Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:altLabel "Mercury"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/797> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Mercury (planet)"@en ;
	skos:definition "The closest planet to the Sun and one of five planets visible with the naked eye. The greatest elongation of Mercury is about 28°, making it visible at most about 112 minutes after sunset or before sunrise. It lies at a mean distance of about 0.39 astronomical units from the Sun. Mercury is just 4,879 km in diameter, about 2.6 times smaller than the Earth. Its orbital period is 87.97 Earth days. Mercury has a high density, 5.4 g cm^-3, with only the Earth having a higher density among the planets. This is largely due to Mercury being composed mainly of heavy metals and rock. One solar day on Mercury lasts the equivalent of 176 Earth days while the sidereal day (the time for 1 rotation in relation to a fixed point) lasts 59 Earth days. Mercury is nearly tidally locked to the Sun and over time this has slowed the rotation of the planet to almost match its orbit around the Sun. Mercury also has the highest orbital eccentricity of all the planets with its distance from the Sun ranging from 46 to 70 million km. Mercury has just 38% the gravity of Earth, this is too little to maintain an atmosphere against solar winds, which blow it away. The surface of Mercury which faces the Sun has temperatures of up to 427°C, whilst on the alternate side this can be as low as -173°C. Mercury's core has more iron than any other planet in the solar system. This has to do with its formation and early life. If the planet formed quickly, increasing temperatures of the evolving Sun could have vaporized much of the existing surface, leaving only a thin shell."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1025> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-10T19:23:39.864Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:altLabel "Mercury manganese stars"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/226> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/128> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/995> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Mercury-manganese stars"@en ;
	skos:definition "Chemically peculiar stars of late B-types. The most distinctive features of Mercury-manganese stars are extreme atmospheric overabundance of Hg (up to 5 dex) and of Mn (up to 3 dex). The origin of abundance anomalies observed in late B-type stars with HgMn peculiarity is still poorly understood. More than two thirds of the HgMn stars are known to belong to spectroscopic binaries with a preference of orbital periods ranging from 3 to 20 days."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/128> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-10-26T19:00:17.903Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:altLabel "B type stars"@en , "B-type stars"@en , "Class B stars"@en , "Type-B stars"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/2051> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/430> ;
	skos:prefLabel "B stars"@en ;
	skos:narrower <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/125> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/127> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/178> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/129> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/126> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1025> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/130> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/142> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/189> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/2> ;
	skos:related <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1589> ;
	skos:definition "A star of spectral type B, whose spectrum is marked by absorption lines of hydrogen; also known as B-type star. B-type optical spectra are characterized by the presence of neutral He lines (mainly He I 4471 Å) at about type B9. He I strengthens up to about B2, then decreases. Ionized helium (mainly He II 4541 Å) first appears at about B0. Most metallic lines are absent or weak, except some absorption lines for the higher ionization states of silicon, oxygen, carbon, and magnesium. These are hot stars with effective temperatures ranging from about 10,000 K at B9 to nearly 30,000 K at B0. They are between 3 and 20 solar masses. Some famous examples include  Rigel, Achernar, and Hadar."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/995> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-03T18:30:21.485Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:altLabel "Cobalt stars"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/226> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Magnetic stars"@en ;
	skos:narrower <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/178> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1025> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/992> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/996> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/33> ;
	skos:definition "A star whose spectral lines show the Zeeman effect."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1026> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-10T19:24:23.072Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/747> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Meridian"@en ;
	skos:definition "An imaginary great circle on the celestial sphere that passes through its poles and the observer's zenith."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/747> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-02T16:48:41.417Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:altLabel "Alt/Az coordinate system"@en , "Horizon (horizon coordinate system)"@en , "Horizon coordinate system"@en , "az/el coordinate system"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/82> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Horizontal coordinate system"@en ;
	skos:narrower <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1026> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1086> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/124> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1765> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1838> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/30> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/2339> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/2340> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/2341> ;
	skos:definition "The coordinate system based on the position of the observer. The horizontal plane is the fundamental plane and the coordinates are altitude and azimuth."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1027> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2021-03-30T14:16:13.640Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:altLabel "Transit circles"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1689> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1708> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Meridian circles"@en ;
	skos:definition "A telescope with a graduated vertical scale, used to measure the declinations of heavenly bodies and sometimes to determine the time of meridian transits."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1689> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-24T17:29:34.053Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/799> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Telescopes"@en ;
	skos:narrower <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1027> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1174> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1105> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/121> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1360> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1800> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1531> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1547> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/634> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1688> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/681> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/687> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/2350> ;
	skos:definition "An instrument used to collect and amplify light or other energy. Refracting telescopes gather light by means of a lens, reflecting telescopes by means of a mirror. Radio telescopes gather radio energy by using an antenna. Telescopes have also been built that can gather X rays, gamma rays, and other forms of energy."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1708> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-04T22:01:56.422Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:altLabel "Transit telescopes"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/799> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Transit instruments"@en ;
	skos:narrower <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1027> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1840> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1841> ;
	skos:definition "An instrument mounted so as to allow it to be pointed only at objects in the sky crossing the local meridian. Also known as transit telescopes."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1028> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1498> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Mesogranulation"@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1498> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-04T15:22:15.205Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1476> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Solar granulation"@en ;
	skos:narrower <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1028> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1662> ;
	skos:related <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1875> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/2102> ;
	skos:definition "The mottled appearance of the solar photosphere, caused by convective cells, resembling granules, which rises from the interior of the Sun. Each granule has a mean size of about 1,000 km and an upward velocity of about 0.5 km/sec. Granules are separated by intergranular walls about 400 K colder. They emerge from the fragments of the preceding granules and their lifetimes are about 20 minutes."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1029> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/437> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Mesopause"@en .

