<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/148> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-24T16:59:27.653Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:altLabel "Beta canis majoris stars"@en , "Beta Cephei stars"@en , "Beta Cepheid variable stars"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/432> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1079> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1307> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1453> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Beta Cephei variable stars"@en ;
	skos:related <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1000> ;
	skos:scopeNote "These stars are usually hot blue-white stars of spectral class B and should not be confused with Cepheid variables, which are named after Delta Cephei and are luminous supergiant stars. -- Wikipedia, https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beta_Cephei_variable"@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1847> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-04T20:47:50.198Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1079> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1799> ;
	skos:prefLabel "ZZ Ceti stars"@en ;
	skos:definition "A member of a class of non-radially pulsating stars that change their brightnesses with periods from 30 seconds to 25 minutes and amplitudes from 0.001 to 0.2 mag in V. Their location on the Hertzsprung-Russell diagram identifies them as white dwarf stars that have entered the instability strip as they evolve along the white dwarf track."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/370> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-05T15:48:57.109Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:altLabel "Al Velorum stars"@en , "Delta Scuti variables"@en , "Dwarf Cepheids"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1079> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1307> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1453> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Delta Scuti variable stars"@en ;
	skos:definition "A member of a class of pulsating stars with periods less than 0.3 days, spectral types A or F, and visual light amplitudes in the range from a few thousands of a magnitude to about 0.8 mag. On the H-R diagram, δ Scuti stars form a group which lies in an instability strip which includes the classical Cepheids at its brightest end and the pulsating white dwarfs at its faintest limit. These stars can show very complex light variations since, while some of them are pulsating in one radial mode only, others may be pulsating simultaneously in several radial and non-radial modes."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/404> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2019-12-03T17:56:31.693Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:altLabel "Double mode variable stars"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1079> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1307> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Double-mode variable stars"@en ;
	skos:narrower <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1876> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1754> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/402> ;
	skos:scopeNote "Not to be confused with \"Double periodic variable stars.\""@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/108> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-05T18:59:52.888Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:altLabel "AGB"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/725> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Asymptotic giant branch"@en ;
	skos:related <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/2100> ;
	skos:definition "A region of the Hertzsprung-Russell diagram populated by evolving low-mass to intermediate-mass stars. These stars have an electron degenerate core of carbon and oxygen surrounded by two burning shells of helium and hydrogen. The H and He-burning shells are activated alternately in the deep layers of the star. An extended and tenuous convection envelope, having a radius of 10^4 - 10^5 times the size of the core, lies above these shells. The loosely bound envelope is gradually eroded by the strong stellar wind, which forms a dusty circumstellar envelope out to several hundreds of stellar radii. The convective envelope, stellar atmosphere, and circumstellar envelope have a rich and changing chemical composition provided by nucleosynthesis processes in the burning shells in the deep interior."@en .

