<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/353> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-03T19:51:46.777Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/739> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/813> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Dark matter"@en ;
	skos:narrower <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/140> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1787> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/265> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/750> ;
	skos:related <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/343> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1091> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/96> ;
	skos:definition "Matter that has no radiation and therefore cannot be detected directly, but whose presence can be inferred from dynamical phenomena produced by its gravitational influence. The existence of dark matter is deduced mainly from the rotational speeds of galaxies, velocities of galaxies in clusters, gravitational lensing by galaxy clusters, and the temperature distribution of hot gas in galaxies and clusters of galaxies. Dark matter plays also a central role in cosmic structure formation. There exists a large number of non-baryonic dark matter candidates. They include, the hypothetical stable particles WIMPs, neutralinos, axions, gravitinos, etc. Among unstable candidates are gravitinos with mild R-parity violation and sterile neutrinos."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1092> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-12-04T18:07:50.917Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:altLabel "NECs"@en , "NEOs"@en , "Near-Earth asteroids"@en , "Near-Earth comets"@en , "Near Earth objects"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1469> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Near-Earth objects"@en ;
	skos:narrower <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/110> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/111> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/36> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/438> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/58> ;
	skos:related <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/280> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/255> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/72> ;
	skos:definition "An asteroid, comet, or large meteoroid whose orbit brings it exceptionally close to the Earth, and which may therefore pose a collision danger. Most such objects are in orbits around the Sun with perihelion distance less than 1.3 astronomical units. "@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/110> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-10-26T18:58:42.748Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:altLabel "Aten asteroids"@en , "Atens"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1092> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Aten group"@en ;
	skos:definition "A member of a class of near-Earth asteroids with perihelion distances between 0.983 and 1.0 astronomical units. It is estimated that 6% of the total number of NEAs are Atens."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/111> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	skos:altLabel "Apohele asteroids"@en , "Apohele group"@en , "Atiras"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1092> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Atira group"@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/36> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-12-03T17:23:52.817Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:altLabel "Amor asteroids"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1092> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Amor group"@en ;
	skos:narrower <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/2182> ;
	skos:definition "A near-Earth asteroid (NEA) with perihelion distances between 1.017 and 1.3 astronomical units. The Amor asteroids approach the orbit of the Earth from beyond, but do not intersect it. Most Amors do cross the orbit of Mars. It is estimated that 32% of the total number of NEAs are Amors. One of the larger Amors is Eros."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/438> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1715> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1092> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Earth trojans"@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/58> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-10-26T18:43:15.170Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:altLabel "Apollo asteroids"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1092> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Apollo group"@en ;
	skos:definition "A member of a class of near-Earth asteroids (NEAs) that have orbital semi-major axes greater than that of the Earth (> 1 astronomical unit) but perihelion distances less than the Earth's aphelion distance (less than 1.017 AU); thus, they cross the Earth's orbit when near the perihelia of their orbits. They are named for the prototype Apollo."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/255> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-10-26T20:06:31.917Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/211> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Close encounters"@en ;
	skos:narrower <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1162> ;
	skos:related <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1092> ;
	skos:definition "In a star cluster, coming across of two stars so closely that their orbits alter by their mutual gravitational attractions. As regards an asteroid or comet, a situation when it crosses the Moon's orbit and approaches the Earth with a risk of collision."@en .

