<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/379> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-10-27T13:38:01.457Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/75> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/831> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Diffuse interstellar bands"@en ;
	skos:definition "Absorption features in the spectrum of stars identified in the ultraviolet, visible, and infrared regions. They have an interstellar origin, but despite extensive efforts, their carrier(s) have not yet been clearly identified."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/831> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-10T17:45:00.477Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/847> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Interstellar absorption"@en ;
	skos:narrower <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/379> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/837> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/843> ;
	skos:definition "The absorption of light from stars and other objects by intervening gas and dust in interstellar space."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/942> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-10T18:37:23.046Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/38> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Luminosity function"@en ;
	skos:definition "Number distribution of stars or galaxies (galaxy) with respect to their absolute magnitudes. The luminosity function shows the number of stars of a given intrinsic luminosity (or the number of galaxies per integrated magnitude band) in a given volume of space."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/380> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-10-27T13:39:05.772Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:altLabel "Translucent interstellar clouds"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/834> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Diffuse interstellar clouds"@en ;
	skos:definition "An interstellar cloud in which hydrogen is completely dissociated and which is less dense and dusty than molecular clouds. In diffuse interstellar clouds photoabsorption of the background ultraviolet (UV) radiation field is an important dissociating and ionizing process. Typical densities and temperatures of diffuse clouds are 10^2 to 10^3 cm^-3 and 20 to 100 K respectively. Because of modest extinctions (≤ 1 mag), photodissociation processes are important in diffuse clouds preventing the formation of larger molecules."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/383> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2019-12-12T21:44:23.913Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:altLabel "Diffuse sky radiation"@en , "Skylight"@en , "Sky radiation"@en , "Diffuse skylight"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/437> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Diffuse radiation"@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/386> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	skos:altLabel "Direct-detection interferometry"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/808> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Direct detection interferometry"@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/387> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2022-06-30T15:03:59.704Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1684> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/489> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Direct imaging"@en ;
	skos:narrower <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/528> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/2369> .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/388> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-05T15:40:10.914Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:altLabel "Dirty snowball theory"@en , "Dirty iceball model"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/280> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Dirty snowball model"@en ;
	skos:definition "A model for a cometary nucleus proposed by Fred Whipple (1950-51), according to which the nucleus is a solid body (a few kilometers across) made up of various ices (frozen water, methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen cyanide) in which dust is embedded. Dust particles are liberated when the ices vaporize as the comet approaches the Sun, and they get blown away by solar radiation pressure, often forming impressive, gently curved dust tails."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/919> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-10T18:17:41.600Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:altLabel "Light-year"@en , "Lightyear"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/395> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Light year"@en ;
	skos:definition "The distance that light travels in one year at about 300,000 km per second, i.e. 9.5 x 10^12 km. It is equal to about 63,000 astronomical units."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/95> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-24T17:15:52.384Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:altLabel "AU"@en , "au"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/395> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Astronomical unit"@en ;
	skos:definition "A unit of length equal to 149,597,870,700 m exactly, with symbol 'au' (re-definition at the International Astronomical Union's 28th General Assembly in Beijing, China, August 20-31). The astronomical unit equals 1.5813 x 10^-5 light-years and 4.8481 x 10^-6 parsecs."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/748> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-09T16:42:57.140Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/396> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Horizontal parallax"@en ;
	skos:definition "The angle under which the radius of the Earth at the place of observation would be seen from a celestial body when it is in the horizon (at the instant of rising or setting). The amount varies with the latitude since the Earth is not exactly spherical, and is greatest at equator."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/40> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-24T17:20:08.801Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:altLabel "Angular distance"@en , "Apparent distance"@en , "Apparent separation"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/85> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Angular separation"@en ;
	skos:definition "Between two points A and B, the angle subtended by lines drawn from an observing point O to A and B."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/405> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	skos:altLabel "Binary galaxies"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/573> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Double galaxies"@en ;
	skos:narrower <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/411> .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/411> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/405> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Dumbbell galaxies"@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/408> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-05T15:41:42.012Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/416> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Draco dwarf galaxy"@en ;
	skos:definition "A dwarf elliptical galaxy that is a satellite of our Galaxy and lies at a distance of about 250,000 light-years from the Galactic center. Its diameter is only about 3,500 light-years, and its absolute magnitude -8.6, making it the least luminous galaxy known."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/409> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-03T20:20:50.881Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:altLabel "Dredge up"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/911> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Dredge-up"@en ;
	skos:definition "A process by which the nucleosynthesis products inside a star are drawn to upper layers of the star."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/41> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-04T22:23:35.302Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/975> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Annual equation"@en ;
	skos:definition "An irregularity in the Moon's orbit, which can amount to 11 degrees in a period of one year. It results from the Sun's disturbing effect on the motion of the Moon due to varying distance between them."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/412> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	skos:altLabel "Infrared cirrus"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/840> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Dust continuum emission"@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/840> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-12-03T20:53:05.349Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:altLabel "Interstellar electromagnetic emissions"@en , "Interstellar infrared emissions"@en , "Interstellar optical emissions"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/847> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Interstellar emissions"@en ;
	skos:narrower <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/835> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1340> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/844> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/412> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/846> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/856> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/857> ;
	skos:scopeNote "Covers all interstellar emissions of electromagnetic radiation."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/417> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-10-27T13:46:43.065Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:altLabel "Dwarf irregular galaxy"@en , "Dwarf irregulars"@en , "Irregular dwarf galaxies"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/416> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/864> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Dwarf irregular galaxies"@en ;
	skos:definition "An irregular galaxy that is much smaller than other irregulars. Dwarf irregulars are generally metal poor and have relatively high fractions of gas. They are thought to be similar to the earliest galaxies that populated the Universe, and are therefore important to understand the overall evolution of galaxies."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/548> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/420> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Fornax dwarf spheroidal galaxy"@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/422> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-03T20:27:00.842Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:altLabel "Gravitational drag"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/669> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Dynamical friction"@en ;
	skos:definition "The gravitational interaction between a relatively massive body and a field of much less massive bodies through which the massive body travels. As a result, the moving body loses momentum and kinetic energy. An example of dynamical friction is the sinking of massive stars to the center of a star cluster, a process called mass segregation. Dynamical friction plays an important role in stellar dynamics. It was first quantified by Chandrasekhar (1943)."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/424> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-24T17:28:29.043Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/429> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/2176> ;
	skos:prefLabel "E+A galaxies"@en ;
	skos:definition "E+A galaxies have strong Balmer absorption lines typical of young stars, but lack optical emission features (e.g. O III 5007) typical of star-forming regions and have metallic absorption lines (e.g. Ca H and K) indicative of an older population of dwarf stars. The presence of two distinct stellar populations and morphological observations suggest that E+A galaxies are the product of a gas-rich galaxy merger."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/429> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-10-30T19:03:54.677Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:altLabel "Early type galaxies"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/573> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Early-type galaxies"@en ;
	skos:narrower <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/424> ;
	skos:definition "In the Hubble classification, galaxies on the left part of the Hubble sequence. Early-type galaxies tend to have redder colors, higher average surface brightnesses, and lower neutral hydrogen content than late-type galaxies. This terminology is based on the obsolete and erroneous idea that elliptical and lenticular galaxies might be evolutionary precursors to spiral and barred spiral galaxies."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/43> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-10-26T18:40:43.142Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/442> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Annular eclipses"@en ;
	skos:definition "A solar eclipse in which the Moon is close the apogee and is, therefore, too small to cover the whole disk of the Sun, leaving a visible edge or ring of sunlight. An annular eclipse can last for 12m 30s at the most."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/525> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/430> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Faint blue stars"@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/8> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-12-17T16:40:45.952Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:altLabel "A supergiants"@en , "A-type supergiants"@en , "A-type supergiant stars"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/431> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/5> ;
	skos:prefLabel "A supergiant stars"@en ;
	skos:related <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/2122> .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/944> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-12-16T15:42:22.137Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:altLabel "Luminous blue variables"@en , "LBV"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/432> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/476> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/460> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Luminous blue variable stars"@en ;
	skos:narrower <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1420> ;
	skos:related <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/2122> ;
	skos:definition "A high-luminosity variable star, which represents a transition phase in the life of a massive star when it evolves off the main sequence to become a supernova. Only about a dozen confirmed luminous blue variable stars are presently known in our Galaxy."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/67> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-10-26T18:44:59.166Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:altLabel "Armil"@en , "Armilla"@en , "Spherical astrolabes"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/433> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Armillary spheres"@en ;
	skos:definition "An ancient instrument, used since ancient times until the Middle ages and later, to determine positions of celestial bodies. It consisted of an assemblage of rings, all circles of the same sphere, designed to represent the positions of the important circles of the celestial sphere."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/93> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-05T15:22:59.988Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:altLabel "Astronomer's sextants"@en , "Framed sextants"@en , "Mural sextants"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/433> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Astronomical sextants"@en ;
	skos:definition "An instrument used mainly in nautical astronomy to determine the angular distances of celestial bodies above the horizon. The sextant consists of a 60° graduated arc, or limb, a small telescope, and two mirrors. Only half of one of the mirrors, the horizon glass, is silvered and, like the telescope, it is fastened to the frame supporting the limb. The other mirror, the index mirror, moves with an index arm pivoted at the center of the arc. The index arm is equipped with a vernier which moves along the limb. An object in direction S can be observed in the telescope through the un-silvered portion of the horizon glass. By moving the index arm, the second object S' is made to coincide with S in the telescope. According to the law of reflection, the angle between S and S' is double the angle between the mirrors. The angular distance between the objects can therefore be obtained from the measurement of angles between the planes of the mirrors."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/795> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/435> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Initial conditions of the universe"@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/916> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/435> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Leptogenesis"@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/499> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-03T21:04:25.421Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/437> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Exosphere"@en ;
	skos:narrower <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/644> ;
	skos:definition "The outermost portion of the Earth's atmosphere. Extremely tenuous, it lies above the ionosphere from a height of about 500 km, to the edge of interplanetary space. Since the mean free path is much greater than the atmospheric scale height, the atoms or molecules never collide with each other."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/764> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-09T16:50:51.069Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/437> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Humidity"@en ;
	skos:definition "Generally, a measure of the water vapor content of the air. Popularly, it is used synonymously with relative humidity."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/900> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	skos:altLabel "Land atmosphere interactions"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/437> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Land-atmosphere interactions"@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/439> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-24T19:31:48.280Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:altLabel "Planet Earth"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/797> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Earth (planet)"@en ;
	skos:related <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/1692> ;
	skos:definition "The third planet from the Sun. At perihelion, it is 147,099,590 km from the Sun, and at aphelion it is 152,096.150 km, whereas its mean distance from the Sun (astronomical unit) is 149,598 x 10^6 km. Its orbital period is 365.2563 days (sidereal year) and its eccentricity 0.017. Other characteristics: axial inclination 23.44°; rotation period 23.934 h (sidereal day); mean density 5.52 g/cm^3; mass 5.974 x 10^24 kg; escape velocity 11.18 km/s; average albedo 0.37.  The Earth's atmosphere consists of 78% nitrogen, 21% oxygen and 0.9% argon, plus carbon dioxide, hydrogen, and other gases in much smaller quantities. The atmospheric pressure at sea level is about 1,000 mbar. The surface average temperature is 15° C, but it varies, on the average, between -50° C (winter, Siberia) and up to + 40° C (summer, Sahara).  Liquid water covers 71% of the surface. Over 5,000 active volcanoes have been registered throughout man's known history. The outer layer of the planet, the lithosphere, is covered with the crust. In the upper mantle and beneath the lithosphere, lies asthenosphere. Convection in the asthenosphere has caused plate tectonics motions and continent drifts. The densest layer of the Earth is its core, about 3000 km to 6400 km beneath the surface, consisting primarily of iron and nickel. This core is believed to be at the origin of the magnetic field, which reaches about 3 x 10^-5 tesla near the equator. It has only one natural satellite, the Moon."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/44> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-04T22:24:16.219Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/975> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Anomalistic month"@en ;
	skos:definition "The time interval of 27.554551 days (27d 13h 18m 33.2s), on average, between two successive passages of the Moon through the  perigee of its orbit."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/49> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-03T18:01:53.179Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/442> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Antumbra"@en ;
	skos:definition "That part of the Moon's shadow that extends beyond the umbra. It is similar to the penumbra in that the Sun is only partially blocked by the Moon. From within the antumbra, the Sun appears larger than the Moon which is seen in complete silhouette. An annular eclipse is seen when an observer passes through the antumbra."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/445> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2022-06-21T19:56:15.906Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
