	skos:prefLabel "Hirayama families"@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/765> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-12-09T15:41:32.193Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/72> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Hungaria group"@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/724> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-09T16:35:32.989Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/725> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Hertzsprung gap"@en ;
	skos:definition "A region of the Hertzsprung-Russell diagram, between the main sequence and the giant branch, occupied by very few stars. It corresponds to a very short period in stellar evolution."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/798> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-10T17:36:44.703Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/725> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Instability strip"@en ;
	skos:definition "A narrow, almost vertical, band on the right hand side of the main sequence in the H-R diagram occupied by many different types of pulsating stars (RR Lyrae, Cepheids, W Virginis, ZZ Ceti). Stars traverse this region at least once after they leave the main sequence. The narrow temperature range of the instability strip corresponds to the stellar effective temperature that can sustain partial ionization zones, capable of maintaining stellar oscillations. The blue (hot) edge of the instability strip pertains to stars with surface temperatures hotter than ~7500 K. Because these stars have partial ionization zones too close to their surface, the pulsation mechanism is not active. The red (cooler) edge of the instability strip is determined by stars with a temperature lower than ~5500 K. In these stars convection prevents the build-up of heat pressure necessary to drive pulsations."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/726> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/808> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Heterodyne interferometry"@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/735> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-02T16:39:58.316Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:altLabel "HVC"@en , "High velocity clouds"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/834> ;
	skos:prefLabel "High-velocity clouds"@en ;
	skos:narrower <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/991> ;
	skos:definition "A population of neutral or partly ionized gas clouds in the Galactic halo which are seen as high-altitude structures in the atomic hydrogen 21 cm emission at high radial velocities (v_LSR > 100 km/sec). They have substantial neutral column densities (> 10^19 cm^-2) and their metallicities range from 0.1 to about 1.0 times solar. The distances to the majority of them remain unknown. They may represent the continuing infall of matter onto the Local Group."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/991> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-10T18:57:44.831Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/990> , <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/735> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Magellanic Stream"@en ;
	skos:definition "A thin trail of gas stretching from the Magellanic System toward our own Galaxy over about 150° on the sky, corresponding to hundreds of thousands of light-years. This gas consists primarily of neutral hydrogen and is thought to have originated from the Large and Small Magellanic Clouds as a result of tidal interactions with the Milky Way."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/776> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2020-11-24T19:33:56.776Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/736> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Hypervelocity stars"@en ;
	skos:definition "A star whose velocity is so great that it will escape the gravitational potential of our Galaxy. Depending on the location and direction of motion, this criterion typically corresponds to a stellar velocity in the Galactic rest frame larger than 400 km s^-1, and up to about 1200 km s^-1. The nature of the hypervelocity stars  (HVSs) spans a wide range of types from OB stars, to metal-poor F-type stars and G/K dwarfs. While there is evidence from many late-type B HVSs in the halo to originate from the Galactic supermassive black hole (SMBH), other HVSs seem to originate from the galactic disk. HVSs can obtain their large velocities from a number of different processes: 1) Tidal disruption of close binary stars by the central SMBH of the Milky Way. In this process one star is captured by the SMBH while the other is ejected at high speed via the gravitational slingshot mechanism. 2) Exchange encounters in other dense stellar environments between hard binaries and massive stars may cause stars to be ejected and escape our Galaxy. 3) Disruption of close binaries via supernova explosions. The runaway velocities of both ejected stars can reach large values when asymmetric supernovae are considered, i.e. when the newborn neutron star receives a momentum kick at birth."@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/738> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	skos:altLabel "High-altitude balloons"@en ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/799> ;
	skos:prefLabel "High altitude balloons"@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/745> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/808> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Holographic interferometry"@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/751> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	skos:broader <http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/814> ;
	skos:prefLabel "Hot intergalactic medium"@en .

<http://astrothesaurus.org/uat/752> a rdfs:Resource , skos:Concept ;
	dcterms:modified "2021-09-27T15:43:58.312Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
	dcterms:contributor <http://editor.vocabs.ands.org.au/user/AAS_Frey.Katie_Admin> ;
